| Vox | main | [MetaversalCorp/Vox](https://github.com/MetaversalCorp/Vox) | Standalone GPU compute dispatch library. Accepts SPIR-V, dispatches on Vulkan (native), DX12 (via SPIRV-CrossŌåÆHLSL), or Metal (via SPIRV-CrossŌåÆMSL). Wired into `compute/COMPUTE_DISPATCH`; replaces the dead ANARI compute path. |
| BoringSSL | main | [google/boringssl](https://github.com/google/boringssl) | Cryptographic backend: X.509 parsing, PEM decoding, SHA-256, RSA/ECDSA signing and verification, `X509_STORE` chain validation. Built statically (`BUILD_SHARED_LIBS=OFF`). Used by the `msf/` module. |
| jwt-cpp | v0.7.0 | [Thalhammer/jwt-cpp](https://github.com/Thalhammer/jwt-cpp) | Header-only C++ library for JWS/JWT creation and verification. BoringSSL-compatible. Installed into the depot via a custom header-copy `INSTALL_COMMAND` (bypassing its problematic `FindOpenSSL` integration since no linking is required). |

**Build-time prerequisites (installed by the developer):**

| Tool | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| CMake 3.20+ | Build system generator, orchestrates the SuperBuild |
| C/C++ compiler (C++17) | MSVC 2022, GCC, or Clang |
| Rust / Cargo | Wasmtime build only (installed via rustup or winget) |
| Python 3 | glslang build-time code generation only |
| Go | BoringSSL build only (`winget install GoLang.Go`) |
| NASM | BoringSSL build only on Windows, for assembly-optimized crypto primitives (`winget install NASM.NASM`; the install path must be added to PATH manually) |
| Git | Cloning dependencies |

**Important:** Rust is a build-time dependency of Wasmtime only. Python is a build-time dependency of glslang only. Go and NASM are build-time dependencies of BoringSSL only. None of these tools run at runtime.

### Decision Rationale

**Why Wasmtime (not Wasmer or wasm3)?** Wasmtime is backed by the Bytecode Alliance (Mozilla, Fastly, Intel, Microsoft). It has the strongest WASI support, production-proven multi-tenancy, fuel metering for CPU budget enforcement, and epoch interruption for cooperative scheduling ŌĆö all features the OMB architecture requires for per-service sandboxing. Wasmer has a similar feature set but less institutional backing. wasm3 is an interpreter (no JIT), unsuitable for production performance.

**Why build Wasmtime from source (not pre-built)?** Wasmtime is not available as a vcpkg port. Pre-built binaries exist on GitHub Releases, but building from source is consistent with all other dependencies and gives full control over version, configuration, and debug symbols. The Rust/Cargo build is automated through CMake's ExternalProject mechanism ŌĆö the developer runs `cmake --build` and Cargo handles the rest.

**Why SPIRV-Tools (not Shaderc or glslang)?** The browser receives SPIR-V bytecode from content providers ŌĆö it doesn't compile shaders from GLSL. So glslang (a GLSL-to-SPIR-V compiler) and Shaderc (Google's glslang wrapper) are authoring tools, not browser-runtime tools. What the browser needs at runtime is validation ŌĆö reject malformed SPIR-V before it reaches the GPU driver (SPIRV-Tools). Cross-compilation (SPIRV-Cross) was removed from the architecture ŌĆö ANARI devices consume SPIR-V natively and handle backend translation internally.

**Why build OpenXR from source (not vcpkg)?** OpenXR is available as `openxr-loader:x64-windows` in vcpkg, but building from source (1) maintains the consistent build-from-source pattern, (2) uses the latest release (1.1.58 vs. vcpkg's 1.1.54), and (3) gives us direct control over build options (static vs. dynamic, with/without Vulkan support). The build is fast (under 1 minute) and has no unusual dependencies.

**Why was SPIRV-Cross removed from Sneeze (and brought back for Vox)?** SPIRV-Cross is a decompiler ŌĆö it translates SPIR-V bytecode back into source-level shader languages (HLSL, GLSL, MSL). The OMB architecture originally included it in Sneeze for cross-compiling shaders to whatever the local GPU requires. After architectural review (OMB Architecture Session 26), it was determined that ANARI devices consume SPIR-V natively and handle backend translation internally ŌĆö the browser never needs to cross-compile shaders itself as a rendering concern. SPIRV-Cross was removed from Sneeze. It was reintroduced when **Vox** (the standalone GPU compute dispatch library) was added, because DX12 doesn't support SPIR-V natively (needs HLSL via SPIRV-Cross) and Metal doesn't support SPIR-V natively (needs MSL via SPIRV-Cross). Vox is a static archive, so its unresolved SPIRV-Cross symbols propagate to whoever links Vox ŌĆö but Sneeze does not need to know this directly. Vox's `vox-config.cmake` locates SPIRV-Cross at Sneeze's configure time (via `SpirvCross_ROOT`) and exposes the libraries through `vox::vox`'s `INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES`, so `target_link_libraries (Sneeze PUBLIC vox::vox)` transitively pulls in the SPIRV-Cross archives. Sneeze's C++ code does not `#include <spirv_cross/...>` directly; the SPIRV-Cross dependency is purely a link-line concern driven by Vox's internals and resolved by Vox's own config.

**Why build SPIRV-Tools from source (not vcpkg)?** SPIRV-Tools is available in vcpkg (`spirv-tools:x64-windows`), but building from source follows the same pattern as ANARI and Wasmtime: consistent version control, full debug symbols when needed, and no surprises from vcpkg port patches.

**Why SPIR-V compute via ANARI instead of SYCL?** The OMB architecture originally specified SYCL for browser-internal parallel compute (physics, audio, proximity, IK). After evaluation and consultation with Neil Trevett (Khronos Group president), SYCL was determined to be impractical for Sneeze's current needs:

- **No SYCL implementation works with MSVC on Windows without replacing the compiler.** Intel oneAPI DPC++ requires its own compiler (`icx`/`dpcpp`), a ~10 GB toolchain, and is optimized for Intel GPUs. AdaptiveCpp (formerly hipSYCL) requires Clang. ComputeCpp is deprecated (Codeplay was acquired by Intel). Replacing the C++ compiler is not acceptable.
- **SYCL targets the wrong abstraction level for a browser engine.** SYCL auto-offloads C++ to GPUs, which trades control for convenience. A browser engine needs explicit control over when and how GPU resources are allocated, dispatched, and synchronized.
- **SPIR-V compute via ANARI achieves the same goal with tools already in the build.** SPIRV-Tools (validation, optimization) is already integrated. Adding glslang for GLSL-to-SPIR-V compilation completes the authoring pipeline. At runtime, compute SPIR-V is handed to ANARI, which routes to whatever GPU backend is available (Vulkan, Metal, DX12) ŌĆö the browser never interacts with GPU compute APIs directly.
- **The compute abstraction remains internal.** Services never see the compute layer ŌĆö it's the browser team's tool. Swapping the underlying ANARI device (or falling back to CPU) requires no changes to service-facing APIs.

Neil Trevett independently recommended this same approach. The decision was made 2026 Q2.

**Compute kernel authoring pipeline:**

1. **Author** compute kernels in GLSL (`#version 450`, Vulkan-flavored). Source files live in `compute/kernels/`.
2. **Compile** to SPIR-V at build time using glslang. Output is `.spv` binary bytecode.
3. **Embed** `.spv` bytecode into the executable using platform-native mechanisms:
   - **Windows:** Win32 resources (`.rc` file, loaded via `FindResource`/`LoadResource`)
   - **Linux:** ELF binary embedding via `objcopy` (symbols: `_binary_*_start`, `_binary_*_end`, `_binary_*_size`)
   - **macOS:** Mach-O section embedding via `ld -sectcreate`
4. **Dispatch** at runtime via **Vox** (`MetaversalCorp/Vox`, Apache 2.0). `COMPUTE_DISPATCH` calls `vox::DEVICE::Create(Backend::Auto)` during construction, which picks the best available backend on the host (Vulkan where drivers are present, DX12 on Windows, Metal on macOS, else null). On each `Dispatch()` call, the embedded SPIR-V for the named kernel is handed to Vox: `CreateKernel()` ŌåÆ `CreateBuffer()` for each `BUFFER_BINDING` ŌåÆ `SetData()` uploads ŌåÆ `SetKernel()` + `SetBuffer()` + `SetPushConstants()` + `Dispatch()` + `Finish()` ŌåÆ `GetData()` reads back non-read-only bindings, then the Vox objects are destroyed.
5. **Fallback** to CPU when Vox returns no device or the GPU path fails (e.g., kernel creation errors, SPIRV-Cross rejects the shader). `COMPUTE_DISPATCH` maintains a registry of C++ kernel implementations keyed by kernel name. Built-in CPU fallbacks mirror the GLSL logic exactly (e.g., `CpuProximityKernel` for `TEST_PROXIMITY`). Callers can register additional CPU kernels via `RegisterCpuKernel()`.

Vox is fully integrated into `COMPUTE_DISPATCH`. Vox and SPIRV-Cross are part of Sneeze's dependency graph: SPIRV-Cross is a tier-0 dep (no predecessors), Vox is tier-1 (depends on SPIRV-Cross) in `.github/workflows/build-platform.yml`, and both have corresponding `deps/spirv-cross.cmake` / `deps/vox.cmake` files plus top-level `ExternalProject_Add` blocks in `CMakeLists.txt`. Vox itself ships a portable `vox-config.cmake` (hand-written template in `Vox/cmake/vox-config.cmake.in`, upstream commit `e70c5f6`) that performs consumer-side SPIRV-Cross discovery from `SpirvCross_ROOT`, so Sneeze just sets the hint and calls `find_package (Vox CONFIG REQUIRED)` ŌĆö no `FindVox` / `FindSpirvCross` module lives in Sneeze. `vox::vox` carries DX12 / Metal / Vulkan / SPIRV-Cross transitively, so `src/CMakeLists.txt` only links the target and the platform-specific libs that are *not* Vox's concern (curl, wasmtime, security frameworks). Sneeze's test suite includes `VoxTest.exe` (direct Vox API exercise, parallels the upstream test) and `ComputeTest.exe` (goes through Vox when available, CPU fallback when not). Vox's legacy `ANARIDevice` constructor parameter is kept for source compat but ignored.

**Shader/kernel authoring language ŌĆö GLSL + glslang (decided):**

**Decision: GLSL + glslang.**

glslang is the Khronos reference SPIR-V compiler. GLSL compute shaders (`#version 450`, `layout()` bindings) are compiled to SPIR-V at build time. glslang builds cleanly with MSVC and CMake, has no external dependencies, and is version-aligned with SPIRV-Tools (pinned to the same Vulkan SDK release tag). It is a build-time-only tool ŌĆö adds zero runtime overhead.

**Why not Slang?** Slang (originally NVIDIA, now under Khronos stewardship) is a more modern shader language with generics, interfaces, modules, and multi-target compilation (SPIR-V, HLSL, MSL, CUDA from one source). Neil Trevett informally characterized glslang as older and Slang as more modern. However:

- The browser's internal compute kernels are simple, well-scoped parallel algorithms (physics, proximity, IK, audio DSP). GLSL is fully sufficient. Generics and modules solve code-reuse problems that emerge at scale ŌĆö not relevant for a small set of focused kernels.
- Slang's multi-target compilation is moot because ANARI handles backend selection. The browser only needs to produce SPIR-V; ANARI routes it to whatever GPU API is available.
- Slang is a heavier dependency (submodules, Python build dep, bundles its own SPIRV-Tools copies requiring deduplication).
- The architecture doc positions Slang as a content-provider authoring tool, not a browser-internal requirement. The browser doesn't recommend any specific authoring tool ŌĆö it accepts valid SPIR-V regardless of what produced it.
- If the kernel codebase grows complex enough to need Slang's features, migration cost is low ŌĆö same SPIR-V output, same embedding pipeline, same ANARI dispatch. Only source files and compiler change.

**glslang is already integrated.** Khronos reference SPIR-V compiler (build-time only). Compiles GLSL compute shaders to SPIR-V bytecode. Same org and release cadence as SPIRV-Tools. Pinned to `vulkan-sdk-1.4.341.0`. No Vulkan SDK dependency ŌĆö ANARI handles compute dispatch at runtime.

**Why RmlUi (not Dear ImGui)?** Dear ImGui is immediate-mode ŌĆö every frame, your code rebuilds the entire UI by calling draw functions. RmlUi is retained-mode ŌĆö you describe the UI in HTML/CSS-like markup, and the library maintains the DOM, handles layout, animations, and event dispatch automatically. For a browser engine with complex, persistent UI (chrome, tabbed interfaces, developer tools, service-provided UI), retained mode is the correct paradigm. RmlUi's HTML/CSS model also aligns with the OMB architecture's intent to let services define UI through standard web-like markup. Single toolkit for all UI surfaces ŌĆö no mixing of two rendering systems.

**Why build RmlUi from source (not vcpkg)?** RmlUi is available in vcpkg, but building from source (1) maintains the consistent build-from-source pattern, (2) gives full control over the font engine configuration (FreeType enabled, see below), and (3) gives full control over which optional features are included (no Lua, no Lottie, no SVG).

**RmlUi dual-context architecture (Sneeze + Artemis).** RmlUi is initialized once per process by Sneeze (`Rml::Initialise()` in `UI_CONTEXT::Initialize()`), but both Sneeze and Artemis create their own independent `Rml::Context` objects. The key API that makes this work is `Rml::CreateContext(name, dimensions, render_interface, text_input_handler)` ŌĆö each context can have its **own** `RenderInterface`. Shared globals (system interface, font engine) are set by Sneeze and serve both sides.

- **Artemis contexts** use an SDL-backed `RenderInterface` for browser chrome: the Inspector, URL bar, menus, toolbars, developer tools. These are application-level UI surfaces that Sneeze never sees.
- **Sneeze contexts** (future) use an ANARI-backed `RenderInterface` for in-world UI: service-provided HTML/CSS overlays composited onto the 3D viewport. This is Phase 4 work.

The Inspector is **entirely Artemis's concern** ŌĆö it is browser chrome, in the same category as the URL bar and menus. Sneeze renders metaverse content inside the viewport; Artemis renders everything outside it. Sneeze never sees the Inspector's RmlUi context, documents, or rendering.

**FreeType font engine.** RmlUi is built with `-DRMLUI_FONT_ENGINE=freetype` and `-DCMAKE_PREFIX_PATH=${LIBS_DIR}/FreeType/install`. FreeType 2.13.3 is a separate Sneeze dependency (`deps/freetype.cmake`), built static with all optional deps disabled. RmlUi links FreeType PRIVATE, so unresolved symbols propagate from the static lib ŌĆö Sneeze links FreeType directly via `${FREETYPE_LIB}` to resolve them. RmlUi's built-in FreeType font engine activates automatically on `Rml::Initialise()`. Both Sneeze and Artemis benefit from the shared font engine ŌĆö it's a global RmlUi interface, set once during init.

**Why build curl from source (not vcpkg)?** curl is available as `curl[ssl]:x64-windows` in vcpkg, but building from source (1) maintains the consistent build-from-source pattern established with ANARI, Wasmtime, SPIR-V, and OpenXR, (2) gives full control over the SSL backend (Schannel vs. OpenSSL ŌĆö we chose Schannel to avoid an OpenSSL dependency), and (3) makes future removal trivial (delete the source directory and remove the CMake references). Built as a static library with no DLLs to manage. The user noted this integration may be temporary.

**Why Schannel (not OpenSSL)?** On Windows, Schannel is the native SSL/TLS implementation ŌĆö it uses the Windows certificate store, requires no CA bundle management, and has zero additional dependencies. OpenSSL would add a ~5 MB dependency and require distributing `libssl.dll` and `libcrypto.dll`. For cross-platform builds, the SSL backend would be platform-appropriate (OpenSSL on Linux, Secure Transport on macOS).

**Why build ANARI from source (not vcpkg)?** We need the `anari_backend` + `helium` libs that Halogen statically links against, and we need both Debug and Release install trees with matching `/MDd` and `/MD` libs respectively. The vcpkg `anari` port installs only the loader, provides no per-config CRT control, and bundles ABI decisions we can't override. Source-build gives us both, and the build is fast now that helide + Embree are disabled.

**Helide is disabled.** `deps/anari-sdk.cmake` passes `-DBUILD_HELIDE_DEVICE=OFF`. Halogen is the sole renderer. Helide (ANARI's reference CPU ray tracer on Embree) is not built because (a) nothing loads it, (b) Embree's deeply nested install paths exceed Windows' 260-char `MAX_PATH` for most checkout locations, and (c) it adds build time. `ANARI_RENDERER`'s constructor takes a library name string with no default ŌĆö caller must specify (e.g. `"halogen"`).

**ANARI install tree contents:**

| Artifact | Role |
|---|---|
| `anari.dll` + `anari.lib` | ANARI core loader (shared ŌĆö unused at runtime since Sneeze links `anari_static`) |
| `anari_static.lib` | ANARI core (static) ŌĆö this is what Sneeze links |
| `anari_backend.lib` + `helium.lib` | Device-implementation libs Halogen statically links against |
| `anari_library_debug.{dll,lib}` | Tiny built-in "debug forwarder" device (logs ANARI calls; NOT helide) |
| `anari_library_sink.{dll,lib}` | Tiny built-in "null sink" device (no-op; NOT helide) |
| `anari_test_scenes.{dll,lib}` | Test scene generator utility |

Both install trees (Release `ANARI-SDK/`, Debug `ANARI-SDK/`) are identical in shape ŌĆö only the CRT (`/MD` vs. `/MDd`) and PDBs differ.

**ANARI static linking.** ANARI core (`anari::anari_static`) is linked statically into Sneeze. ANARI device libraries (Halogen, etc.) are always built as shared plugins by design in the SDK ŌĆö not something we can change. At runtime, `ANARI_RENDERER` calls `anariLoadLibrary(sLibrary.c_str())` to load the chosen device DLL; on Windows that's `anari_library_<name>.dll`, which Artemis's POST_BUILD step copies from `${SNEEZE_LIBS_DIR}/Halogen/install/bin/` into the Artemis output directory.

**Why nlohmann/json?** General-purpose JSON parsing for both engine and application use. Header-only (no link libraries, no DLLs), MIT license, single-header deployment. Exposed as PUBLIC on the Sneeze target so Artemis can `#include <nlohmann/json.hpp>` without additional CMake configuration.

**Why BoringSSL (not OpenSSL) for the crypto backend?** The `msf/` module needs X.509 parsing, SHA-256, RSA/ECDSA signature verification, and certificate chain validation. OpenSSL and BoringSSL both expose the same API surface for these primitives. BoringSSL was chosen because (1) it has a stricter, better-maintained ASN.1 parser (it rejects malformed X.509 v1 certs that carry v3 extensions ŌĆö a real defense-in-depth win), (2) it builds cleanly and fast with CMake on all three platforms, (3) it is a single static library with no license-text or runtime DLL distribution concerns, and (4) Google actively maintains it for Chrome / Android / Cronet, which is where most of the JWS ecosystem's battle-testing happens. The trade-off is that BoringSSL has no stable API contract ŌĆö consumers must pin to a commit. Acceptable: it lives in the depot, and the depot is pinned anyway.

**Why jwt-cpp?** Header-only C++ JWS/JWT library. It does exactly one thing well: takes a payload + private key + algorithm and produces a compact serialization; takes a compact serialization + public key and verifies the signature. It works with both OpenSSL and BoringSSL (since they share API). No link-time dependency, no DLL to ship. We bypass its CMake `find_package(OpenSSL)` glue (it chokes on BoringSSL's non-standard headers) and just copy the headers into the depot with a custom `INSTALL_COMMAND`. Link `src/context/msf/` directly against BoringSSL; jwt-cpp just provides header templates.

**Why SHA-256 of SPKI as the organizational identifier?** The identity of an organization that signs MSF/MSS files must survive (a) certificate renewals (same key, new expiry date), (b) signing-tool changes, and (c) independent computation by any consumer (engine or HTML viewer). Hashing the `SubjectPublicKeyInfo` (the raw DER public-key blob inside the X.509 cert) satisfies all three: the key is stable across renewals with the same key pair, the hash is deterministic, and both BoringSSL (`i2d_PUBKEY`) and the Web Crypto API (`crypto.subtle.importKey("spki", ...)` with access to raw SPKI bytes via the ASN.1 parser) produce byte-identical SPKI representations. Verified end-to-end: `482cda4c2b6c2a81f46a39ec4232f140b24b439dba4b6040b4b7610506c490b7` is the fingerprint of the test provider cert as computed by the engine, the signing tool, and the HTML viewer.

**Why Halogen (Filament-based ANARI device)?** Halogen (`MetaversalCorp/Halogen`) is an ANARI device implementation (`anari_library_halogen.dll`) built on top of Google's Filament rendering engine (`MetaversalCorp/filament`). It provides GPU-accelerated PBR rendering through the ANARI abstraction and is Sneeze's sole renderer. Filament was chosen for its production-quality PBR pipeline (clustered forward renderer, Cook-Torrance BRDF, IBL, PCSS shadows, HDR post-processing), cross-platform backend support (OpenGL, Vulkan, Metal), and proven mobile performance (Android, iOS). Halogen is developed by Jonathan Hale (Squareys).

**Halogen dependency chain ŌĆö Filament, ANARI-SDK, Halogen all track `SNEEZE_CONFIG`.** Debug outer ŌåÆ Debug filament + Debug anari-sdk + Debug halogen; Release outer ŌåÆ all three Release. No shadows, no always-Release pinning. The whole chain is "normal" ŌĆö the same build rules every other dep follows.

The chain has **two** ExternalProject targets (ANARI-SDK is described earlier in this section):

1. **`filament`** (`deps/filament.cmake`) ŌĆö clones `MetaversalCorp/filament.git`. Tracks `SNEEZE_CONFIG`. On Windows passes `USE_STATIC_CRT=OFF` + `DIST_DIR=x86_64/md` ŌåÆ produces `/MD` (Release) or `/MDd` (Debug) libs. Vulkan backend enabled. Samples + tests disabled. Installs to `libs/filament/install/lib/x86_64/md/`. Consumed only by Halogen. Config is pinned to the outer `SNEEZE_CONFIG` both by `-DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=${SNEEZE_CONFIG}` in CMAKE_ARGS **and** by explicit `BUILD_COMMAND ${CMAKE_COMMAND} --build <BINARY_DIR> --config ${SNEEZE_CONFIG}` + matching `INSTALL_COMMAND` ŌĆö because multi-config generators (Visual Studio, Xcode) ignore `CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE` at configure time and `ExternalProject_Add` otherwise inherits a stale outer `--config` into the inner build.

2. **`halogen`** (`deps/halogen.cmake`) ŌĆö clones `MetaversalCorp/Halogen.git`. Tracks `SNEEZE_CONFIG`, same `BUILD_COMMAND` / `INSTALL_COMMAND` override pattern. On Windows the CRT is pinned per-config via a generator expression: `-DCMAKE_MSVC_RUNTIME_LIBRARY=MultiThreaded$<$<CONFIG:Debug>:Debug>DLL`, which picks `/MDd` for Debug and `/MD` for Release ŌĆö matching Filament's CRT and the outer Sneeze build. `CMAKE_POLICY_DEFAULT_CMP0091=NEW` makes `CMAKE_MSVC_RUNTIME_LIBRARY` authoritative. Depends on `filament` + `anari-sdk`, both at matching config. Produces `anari_library_halogen.dll` + its import lib, installs to `libs/Halogen/install/{bin,lib}/`. **Debug Halogen also imports the Release `matc.exe`** ŌĆö see the `FILAMENT_MATC` override paragraph below.

**The key Filament build flag ŌĆö `FILAMENT_SHORTEN_MSVC_COMPILATION=OFF` on Debug.** Filament's `FILAMENT_SHORTEN_MSVC_COMPILATION` (default ON on MSVC) appends `/D_ITERATOR_DEBUG_LEVEL=0` to `CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS_DEBUG` and also enables `/MP` ŌĆö a compile-time perf tweak that produces a hybrid CRT state (`/MDd` + `_IDL=0`) no downstream consumer can link against without matching it exactly. `deps/filament.cmake` turns this OFF on Debug so filament Debug uses standard `/MDd` + `_IDL=2`, which Halogen Debug and Sneeze Debug can link against cleanly. Cost: losing `/MP` (multi-processor compilation) on the filament Debug build ŌĆö a minor one-time dep-build speed hit. The CRT match is what matters.

**Debug Halogen imports the Release `matc` ŌĆö Release filament is a prerequisite for Debug Halogen.** Halogen's build compiles 6 material source files (`.mat` ŌåÆ `.filamat` + generated C header) by invoking `matc.exe`, Filament's material compiler. Debug `matc` on Windows runs **10ŌĆō100├Ś slower** than Release `matc`: the SPIR-V optimizer's inliner walks `std::vector<uint32_t>` hot paths, which MSVC's Debug STL (`_ITERATOR_DEBUG_LEVEL=2`) transforms into heavy iterator-validation code at every access, and the unoptimized codegen compounds the hit. Pre-fix, a full Debug Halogen build took **70+ minutes** and spammed ~12 000 spirv-opt inliner warnings. Post-fix: **<2 minutes, zero warnings.** Wire-up:

- `deps/halogen.cmake` checks, at configure time, for `${SNEEZE_BUILD_ROOT}/release/libs/filament/install/bin/matc${CMAKE_EXECUTABLE_SUFFIX}` whenever `SNEEZE_CONFIG == Debug` and not cross-compiling. If the binary is missing, configure halts with `FATAL_ERROR` and the exact platform-specific command to run first (`scripts/build-windows.ps1 -Deps -Only filament -Config Release`, or the `--config Release` equivalents on Linux/macOS).
- If present, `halogen.cmake` passes `-DFILAMENT_MATC=<release-matc-path>` into Halogen's CMake configure. Halogen's `src/CMakeLists.txt` does `find_program(FILAMENT_MATC matc HINTS ${FILAMENT_SDK_DIR}/bin)`, which is a no-op when the cache variable is already set ŌĆö the preset value wins. No Halogen-side code change needed.
- The Release `matc.exe` links the Release CRT (`MSVCP140.dll`, not `MSVCP140D.dll`), so it runs standalone during Debug configures regardless of the outer toolset state. And since `matc` only reads `.mat` source and writes `.filamat` + headers, there's no ABI concern running it from a Debug build context.
- Release filament's own build emits Release `matc` as a side effect of the standard filament build ŌĆö no extra build step, no extra ExternalProject, no special flags. Debug filament still builds its own Debug `matc` (part of Filament's native `IS_HOST_PLATFORM` target graph), but Halogen Debug never invokes it. The Debug `matc` binary is harmless dead weight at ~60 MB.
- Cross-compile builds (iOS, Android) skip the prereq check. They rely on Filament's existing `IMPORT_EXECUTABLES` / `ImportExecutables-Release.cmake` mechanism ŌĆö Release filament is built on the host first (CI's host job), then its `ImportExecutables-Release.cmake` is handed to the target-config filament build via `IMPORT_EXECUTABLES_HOST_FILE`. Halogen picks up the same imported `matc` through Filament's SDK install tree.
- Standalone Halogen clones (outside the Sneeze umbrella) are unaffected. Halogen's `cmake/DownloadFilament.cmake` auto-downloads Google's prebuilt Filament SDK tarball into `external/filament/` if `FILAMENT_SDK_DIR` isn't populated ŌĆö and those prebuilt tarballs ship Release `matc`. The `-DFILAMENT_MATC=...` override in `deps/halogen.cmake` is a Sneeze-specific layer that doesn't interfere.

**Runtime ABI.** ANARI's C ABI (`anariLoadLibrary` + function pointers; no C++ objects or STL containers cross the DLL boundary) means Debug Sneeze loading Release Halogen (or vice versa) is still safe ŌĆö but with both built at matching config, Halogen Debug ships with PDBs and is fully steppable in the debugger, which is the point of building it Debug at all.

**Halogen must override `anari_DIR`, not just `ANARI_ROOT`.** `find_package(anari CONFIG)` caches `anari_DIR` on first successful resolve. On subsequent reconfigures, a new `-DANARI_ROOT=...` hint is silently ignored ŌĆö CMake reuses the cached `anari_DIR`. `deps/halogen.cmake` therefore passes **both** `-DANARI_ROOT=${_halogen_anari_root}` *and* `-Danari_DIR=${_halogen_anari_root}/lib/cmake/anari-0.16.0` to force the value on every reconfigure. The version number in the path (`0.16.0`) matches ANARI-SDK's install subdir and must be bumped if ANARI upgrades.

**Halogen tracks `master`.** Pin to a specific commit hash once the integration stabilizes. The Filament fork tracks `main`.

**Vox GPU Compute Library.** Vox (`MetaversalCorp/Vox`, Apache 2.0) is a standalone library that dispatches SPIR-V compute shaders across Vulkan, DX12, and Metal. ANARI does not and will not support compute shaders ŌĆö Vox fills that gap.

**Vox architecture.** Polymorphic C++ with abstract base classes (`DEVICE`, `BUFFER`, `KERNEL`) and derived implementations per backend (`VULKAN_DEVICE`, `DX12_DEVICE`, `METAL_DEVICE`). Static factory: `DEVICE::Create(Backend::Auto)` selects the best available backend. Callers only see the abstract types.

| Backend | SPIR-V Handling | Cross-compiler | Platform |
|---------|----------------|----------------|----------|
| Vulkan  | Native (no translation) | None | Windows, Linux |
| DX12    | SPIRV-Cross ŌåÆ HLSL ŌåÆ D3DCompile | spirv-cross-hlsl | Windows |
| Metal   | SPIRV-Cross ŌåÆ MSL ŌåÆ MTLLibrary | spirv-cross-msl | macOS |

**Vox key implementation details (learned during DX12 testing):**

- **SPIRV-Cross binding remapping.** SPIRV-Cross preserves original SPIR-V binding numbers when assigning HLSL registers and MSL buffer indices. Example: `layout(binding = 1) writeonly buffer` becomes `register(u1)` in HLSL (not `u0`). Both the DX12 and Metal backends use SPIRV-Cross reflection (`get_decoration(res.id, spv::DecorationBinding)`, `get_automatic_msl_resource_binding()`) after compilation to build root signatures / set buffer indices at the correct slots.
- **DX12 root descriptors.** Vox uses root SRV/UAV descriptors (not descriptor tables) for buffer binding. Root SRV works with `ByteAddressBuffer`, root UAV works with `RWByteAddressBuffer` ŌĆö both of which SPIRV-Cross generates for unbounded storage buffer arrays. This avoids needing a CBV/SRV/UAV descriptor heap entirely.
- **DX12 three-heap buffer model.** DX12 buffers have three D3D12 resources: upload (CPUŌåÆGPU), default (GPU-only), readback (GPUŌåÆCPU). `SetData` writes to upload + a CPU shadow buffer. `GetData` returns shadow data before GPU dispatch, readback heap data after. `Finish()` marks buffers as having GPU results.
- **Metal entry point renaming.** SPIRV-Cross may rename the entry point (e.g., `main` ŌåÆ `main0` in MSL, since `main` is reserved). Vox uses `get_cleansed_entry_point_name()` to get the actual MSL function name.
- **Vulkan needs no SPIRV-Cross.** Vulkan consumes SPIR-V natively. Descriptor set layout uses 16 hardcoded storage buffer bindings (valid superset) and 128-byte push constant range (Vulkan spec minimum). No binding remapping occurs.

**Vox test status:** VoxTest.exe passes 14/14 on DX12:
- Device creation (auto-selects DX12 on Windows)
- Buffer round-trip (SetData ŌåÆ GetData, 4 floats)
- Null backend handling (Metal on Windows ŌåÆ nullptr)
- Full SPIR-V dispatch: `test_proximity.comp` compiled to `.spv` by glslangValidator, loaded at runtime, cross-compiled SPIR-VŌåÆHLSL by SPIRV-Cross, compiled to DXBC by D3DCompile, dispatched on GPU with push constants, results verified (3.000, 4.000, 5.000, 1.732). Metal backend untested (needs macOS). Vulkan backend untested on Windows (DX12 preferred by `Backend::Auto`).

**Vox in the depot.** Added as `deps/vox.cmake` with its own `ExternalProject_Add`, included by `deps/CMakeLists.txt` and ordered via `add_dependencies(vox spirv-cross)`. Configured with `-DSpirvCross_ROOT=${LIBS_DIR}/SPIRV-Cross/install` and `-DBUILD_TESTING=OFF`. Source cloned to `deps/repos/Vox/`. Per-config install at `deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/libs/Vox/install/`.

### MSF (Signing and Verification)

The `msf/` module implements [RFC 7515 JSON Web Signature](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7515) in compact serialization form, used to sign and verify `.msf` (Metaversal Spatial Fabric) files ŌĆö signed JSON that describes a spatial fabric and the services it aggregates. There is a single `.msf` format (no separate `.mss`).

MSF files are signed JSON wrapped as JWS compact serialization (`<header>.<payload>.<signature>`), with the full X.509 certificate chain embedded in the `x5c` header claim. The browser verifies signature + chain before trusting any content.

**JWS stack:**

| Layer | Library | Role |
|-------|---------|------|
| X.509 parse, PEM decode, hashing, RSA/ECDSA | BoringSSL | Crypto primitives |
| Chain validation (trust store, expiry) | BoringSSL (`X509_STORE`) | Platform root trust |
| JWS compact serialization + signing | jwt-cpp (header-only) | JWS/JWT builder |
| Payload shape | nlohmann/json | JSON model |

**Key architectural decisions:**

- **Identity = SHA-256 of leaf public key (SPKI).** Not the cert's fingerprint (which changes on renewal) ŌĆö the public key's. The same org can re-issue certs without changing its identity, as long as the key pair is preserved. Engine and viewer compute this identically.
- **Algorithms supported.** RS256 / RS384 / RS512 (RSA-PKCS1-v1_5) and ES256 / ES384 / ES512 (ECDSA). The HTML viewer also supports PS256/384/512 (RSA-PSS) via Web Crypto. The Sign CLI defaults to RS256.
- **Single unified class.** `MSF` handles the full lifecycle: parsing, signing, verification (signature and chain as separate explicit steps), certificate management, and typed payload access. `MSF::CHAIN` handles X.509 chain validation and exposes public static utilities for certificate operations so `MSF` has no direct BoringSSL dependency.
- **Parse separated from verify.** `MSF::Parse()` populates all data (payload, cert info, fingerprint) without performing any cryptographic validation. `VerifySignature()` and `VerifyChain()` are explicit follow-up calls. This allows consumers to inspect MSF content before deciding whether to verify.
- **Integrated into the Sneeze static library.** `src/context/msf/*.cpp` is part of the `Sneeze` CMake target; BoringSSL's `libcrypto` is linked `PUBLIC` and jwt-cpp headers are on the public include interface. Consumers just `target_link_libraries(... Sneeze)` ŌĆö see `tests/JwsTest` and `tools/SignMsf`. The depot is driven by `deps/boringssl.cmake` + `deps/jwt-cpp.cmake` in Jonathan's superbuild, with matching `src/cmake/FindBoringSSL.cmake` and `src/cmake/FindJwtCpp.cmake` modules.

**Tools produced by the JWS work:**

- **`tools/SignMsf/`** ŌĆö CLI tool (`SignMsf.exe`) for service providers. Usage: `SignMsf --payload foo.json --key provider-key.pem --cert provider-cert.pem --chain ca-cert.pem --alg RS256 --out foo.mss`. Produces a compact-serialization JWS string ready to publish.
- **`tools/MsfViewer/`** ŌĆö fully self-contained, offline HTML/JS viewer (`index.html`). Accepts `.msf`/`.mss` via drag-and-drop, paste, or file picker. Parses the JWS header, decodes each cert in `x5c` using a hand-rolled ASN.1 DER parser (so there's no CDN or bundler dependency), verifies the signature with Web Crypto, computes the leaf fingerprint matching the engine, and displays structured MSS fields with pass/warn/fail status banners. A companion `test-headless.mjs` script (Node `webcrypto`) verifies the same logic without a browser. Ships with `sample-mss.json` and a signed `sample.mss`.

**Test certificates.** `tests/certs/` contains self-signed CA, provider, and expired certs generated by `tests/GenCerts.cpp` (a one-shot utility ŌĆö `GenCerts.exe` is built once, then the output is committed to the repo). All certs are X.509 v3 (required by BoringSSL).

### Known Gotchas

- **cmake must be on PATH.** Cargo's Wasmtime build.rs spawns cmake as a subprocess. cmake must be on the system PATH, not just invocable by full path.
- **Wasmtime submodules are skipped.** The SuperBuild sets `GIT_SUBMODULES ""` for Wasmtime to avoid cloning large test suite repos. Only the main repo is needed for the C API.
- **Wasmtime conf.h is generated by Cargo.** The `wasmtime/conf.h.in` template in the source headers is not usable directly. The Cargo build generates the real `conf.h` in a hashed build output directory. The SuperBuild's install script globs for this and overlays it on top of the source headers.
- **SPIRV-Tools requires Python at configure time.** The build uses Python to auto-generate C++ tables from the SPIR-V grammar JSON. Python 3 must be on PATH.
- **Windows Store python alias.** On Windows, `python.exe` may redirect to the Microsoft Store instead of a real Python installation. Disable in **Settings > Apps > Advanced app settings > App execution aliases**.
- **OpenXR loader stderr diagnostics are suppressed.** The loader writes alarming messages to stderr when no XR runtime is installed. `XrRuntime.cpp` sets `XR_LOADER_DEBUG=none` to suppress these.
- **Static library compile definitions.** `CURL_STATICLIB` and `RMLUI_STATIC_LIB` must be defined when compiling code that includes curl or RmlUi headers. The CMakeLists.txt handles this automatically.
- **RmlUi "No font face defined" warnings.** With FreeType enabled, RmlUi warns when a context renders text without any loaded fonts. These warnings are cosmetic and disappear once `Rml::LoadFontFace()` is called with a real TTF/OTF (Artemis does this for browser chrome; Sneeze will do it for in-world UI).
- **libcurl uses Schannel (Windows native SSL).** No OpenSSL dependency. On Linux/macOS, curl would need OpenSSL or the platform's native SSL.
- **SDL pixel format must match ANARI byte layout (Artemis-side).** ANARI's `ANARI_UFIXED8_RGBA_SRGB` writes R,G,B,A bytes. On little-endian Windows, `SDL_PIXELFORMAT_ABGR8888` matches. This is Artemis's concern, not Sneeze's ŌĆö the engine has no SDL3 dependency.
- **`dwmapi` is no longer used by the compositor.** The old self-paced compositor called `DwmFlush()` for frame pacing. The new job-based compositor does not call `DwmFlush()` ŌĆö frame pacing is now implicit in Filament's vsync wait inside `beginFrame()`. `dwmapi` may still be linked for other purposes but is no longer a compositor dependency.
- **`winmm.lib` is linked on Windows.** The engine metronome calls `timeBeginPeriod(1)` / `timeEndPeriod(1)` to guarantee 1ms sleep resolution for `std::this_thread::sleep_for`. Without this, Windows defaults to ~15.6ms granularity. Linked via `#pragma comment (lib, "winmm.lib")` in `Engine.cpp`.
- **NETWORK shutdown race condition.** `NETWORK::Impl::~Impl()` deletes all leaked FILEs first, then waits for `m_umpAsset` to drain naturally via `while (m_umpAsset.size() > 0) std::this_thread::sleep_for(1ms);` ŌĆö this spin-wait is **outside** the `m_mutex` lock_guard scope (putting it inside deadlocks because `Asset_Close` needs the same mutex to erase from the map). The `sleep_for` inside the loop is critical ŌĆö an empty `while (m_umpAsset.size() > 0);` loop gets optimized away by the compiler in Release builds because `m_umpAsset` has no observable side effects in the loop body (it's not `volatile` and the compiler can't see cross-thread mutations). The 1ms sleep provides both a compiler-visible side effect and CPU yield. This pattern exists because in-flight fetch jobs may set `m_pAsset_Fetch = nullptr` on the ASSET before the network destructor can cancel the fetch ŌĆö the asset then misses its `Cancel()` call and must drain via its normal `FetchComplete` -> `Detach` -> `Asset_Close` path.
- **NETWORK::FILE listener callback after Close() ŌĆö KNOWN BUG.** When `FABRIC::Impl` calls `pFile->Close()` after receiving `OnFileReady`, the `m_pListener` pointer inside `FILE::Impl` is not nulled. If the network inspector later attaches to the same FILE (via `Attach()`), the ASSET may re-trigger `OnFileReady` on the stale listener pointer, causing re-parsing of the MSF and duplicate container creation. Identified during Phase 3 MSF loading integration. The fix is to null `m_pListener` in `FILE::Impl::Pending_Close()` after `Detach()`. Dean is studying and fixing this himself.
- **Build script PCH clearing caused full rebuilds.** `scripts/build-windows.ps1` previously called `Clear-SneezePrecompiledHeaders` unconditionally on every invocation, forcing a full rebuild of the entire Sneeze library even for incremental changes. Fixed: the call is now conditional on `-Fresh` or `-Rebuild` flags only. Day-to-day `.\scripts\build-windows.ps1` no longer triggers unnecessary full recompiles.
- **Filament single-thread constraint.** Filament's API is not thread-safe. All Filament API calls for a given engine instance must be made from a single dedicated thread ŌĆö not just create/destroy, but all calls including `beginFrame`, `render`, `endFrame`. Filament offloads GPU work to an internal render thread, but the caller-facing API is a serial command queue. Halogen creates a single shared Filament Engine, so all ANARI calls across all viewports must be serialized onto one compositor agent (agent 0). Multiple agents calling `anariRenderFrame` concurrently against the same Filament engine crash. **Confirmed empirically:** 3 compositor agents + 3 windows = crash inside `anariRenderFrame`; 1 compositor agent = stable, tabs and windows open/close cleanly. Pool size reduced from 2 to 1. `POOL_CYCLE::Grab()` still routes `kSTATE_CREATE` and `kSTATE_DESTROY` exclusively to agent 0, but with a single agent this is now trivially satisfied.
- **Filament vsync scaling problem.** Filament's Vulkan backend hardcodes `VK_PRESENT_MODE_FIFO_KHR` (vsync ON) in `VulkanPlatformSwapChainImpl.cpp` line 221. FIFO blocks `beginFrame()` until vsync releases a swapchain image (~16.67ms at 60 Hz). This wait is inside `anariRenderFrame`, not `anariFrameReady` (which returns instantly). With N viewports rendered sequentially on one thread, each `anariRenderFrame` incurs its own vsync wait, so total frame time is N ├Ś 16ms. Ten viewports = 6 FPS each. **Proposed solutions** (documented in `AnariRenderer.cpp` header comment): (1) **MAILBOX present mode** ŌĆö modify `MetaversalCorp/filament` to use `VK_PRESENT_MODE_MAILBOX_KHR` instead of `FIFO_KHR`; mailbox doesn't tear or block, GPU renders as fast as it can, only latest frame shown at vsync; compositor would need its own frame pacing via the metronome; (2) **Offscreen readback path** ŌĆö render to ANARI framebuffers without swapchains, Artemis presents via SDL; this path already exists as the non-native-surface fallback; (3) **Hybrid** ŌĆö foreground viewport gets native surface, background viewports render offscreen. No solution implemented yet.
- **Console window for Win32 app.** Artemis calls `AllocConsole()` + `freopen_s()` at the top of `WinMain()` to create a console for `fprintf(stdout/stderr)` output. This is a temporary debug aid; it will be made a selectable option via the title bar menu once the menu is restored. Adding `AllocConsole()` does not change the application's subsystem ŌĆö it remains a Win32 GUI app (`/SUBSYSTEM:WINDOWS`). The console is an auxiliary window.
- **Do NOT delete `deps/builds/<platform>/<config>/build/` for day-to-day rebuilds.** That directory holds the SuperBuild's ExternalProject stamp files (tracking which deps have been cloned, configured, built, and installed). Deleting it loses those stamps, forcing CMake to re-run all dependency steps (5+ minutes even though the `libs/` tree is intact). `-Rebuild` uses `cmake --build --target clean --config <cfg>` against the existing `builds/<platform>/build/` tree to drop the current config's compiled artifacts, then wipes `builds/<platform>/install/<cfg>/`. This keeps the configured CMake state intact (`CMakeCache.txt`, `CMakeFiles/`, generated `.sln`/`.vcxproj`) so an open Visual Studio solution doesn't need to reload, and leaves the non-selected config's intermediates + install tree alone. A Release rebuild cannot destroy a Debug install (and vice versa), and the deps tree is never touched. If `-Rebuild` runs against a tree that has never been configured, the script falls back to a full configure + build.
- **Deleting `deps/builds/<platform>/<config>/libs/` triggers full rebuild for that config.** All dependencies will be re-configured, re-built, and re-installed (45-90 minutes). Source clones in `deps/repos/` are preserved.
- **Deleting `deps/repos/` re-clones every dependency** (~2 GB of git history, ~10 minutes). Rarely needed ŌĆö only when a dep's upstream has force-pushed its tag.
- **Filament is the heaviest dependency.** First Release build takes 15-30 minutes; first Debug build ~25-45 minutes. Incremental rebuilds are fast. Both repos use `GIT_SHALLOW ON`. **A full Debug Halogen workflow requires both configs to be built** ŌĆö Release filament's `matc.exe` is imported by Debug Halogen (see Halogen dep-chain section). The usual first-time sequence is Release-then-Debug; `-All` / `--all` defaults to Release, so running it once for each config in that order "just works."
- **Halogen DLL must be copied to Artemis output.** Artemis's POST_BUILD step copies `anari_library_halogen.dll` from `${SNEEZE_LIBS_DIR}/Halogen/install/bin/` alongside the executable (same step also copies `wasmtime.dll`). Filament itself has no separate runtime DLL at the Sneeze/Artemis boundary ŌĆö the `anari_library_halogen.dll` statically links the bits of Filament it needs.
- **Filament + Halogen track `SNEEZE_CONFIG`** (Debug-on-Debug, Release-on-Release). `deps/filament.cmake` disables `FILAMENT_SHORTEN_MSVC_COMPILATION` on Debug to prevent CRT mismatch (`/D_ITERATOR_DEBUG_LEVEL=0` injection). `deps/halogen.cmake` pins MSVC CRT to `/MDd` for Debug + `/MD` for Release via a generator expression.
- **Debug Halogen uses the Release `matc.exe`.** `deps/halogen.cmake` preseeds `FILAMENT_MATC` to `<SNEEZE_BUILD_ROOT>/release/libs/filament/install/bin/matc.exe` when `SNEEZE_CONFIG=Debug`. This collapses Debug Halogen's material compile from 70+ min and 12 k warnings down to <2 min and zero warnings (Debug matc is 10-100x slower than Release on Windows due to `_ITERATOR_DEBUG_LEVEL=2` + unoptimized codegen on vector-heavy SPIR-V optimizer passes). Configure halts with `FATAL_ERROR` if Release filament isn't built yet, with a platform-specific "run this first" hint. **Release filament is therefore a prerequisite for Debug Halogen.** Cross-compile builds skip the check (they use filament's standard `IMPORT_EXECUTABLES` cross-compile path instead).
- **`ExternalProject_Add` + multi-config generators ignore `-DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=...` in `CMAKE_ARGS`.** Visual Studio / Xcode are multi-config: `CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE` is ignored at configure time, the config is selected at build time via `cmake --build --config <cfg>`. By default, `ExternalProject_Add`'s build step inherits the outer build's `--config`, so the inner build picks up whatever `--config` happens to be active rather than `SNEEZE_CONFIG`. Pin the inner config by explicitly overriding `BUILD_COMMAND` + `INSTALL_COMMAND` to pass `--config ${SNEEZE_CONFIG}` literally. Used for filament + halogen (and any other dep that uses Visual Studio's multi-config generator internally).
- **`find_package(<pkg> CONFIG)` caches `<pkg>_DIR` and skips re-search.** Once `find_package` successfully resolves, the resolved path is written to CMakeCache.txt as `<pkg>_DIR`. On subsequent reconfigures, `find_package` finds the cached value and returns immediately without re-searching ŌĆö even if the hint variable (`<pkg>_ROOT` or `<PKG>_ROOT`) changed. Passing `-D<pkg>_DIR=...` explicitly overrides the cache. This is exactly why `deps/halogen.cmake` passes `-Danari_DIR=${_halogen_anari_root}/lib/cmake/anari-0.16.0` alongside `-DANARI_ROOT=...` ŌĆö without the direct override, stale caches from prior configure attempts silently resolve to the wrong ANARI install.
- **Halogen C++20 vs Sneeze C++17.** Filament compiles with `/std:c++latest`. Since it's an ExternalProject, this is isolated. Sneeze code that includes Filament headers must compile them under C++17. If any public headers use C++20 features, bump Sneeze to C++20 or isolate the includes.
- **Filament bundles its own spirv-tools/glslang/spirv-cross.** These are built inside Filament's `third_party/` tree. They do not conflict with Sneeze's separate copies.
- **CMP0144 policy.** `src/CMakeLists.txt` sets `cmake_policy(SET CMP0144 NEW)` to suppress the warning about `ANARI_ROOT` variable being ignored by `find_package`. The policy tells CMake to respect uppercase `<PACKAGENAME>_ROOT` variables.
- **BoringSSL rejects X.509 v1 certs that carry v3 extensions.** `X509_new()` defaults to version 1; if you add v3 extensions (Basic Constraints, Subject Key Identifier, Key Usage) without calling `X509_set_version(pCert, 2)`, the resulting cert encodes as ASN.1 but is malformed. BoringSSL's `PEM_read_bio_X509` rejects it with `ASN.1 encoding routines:OPENSSL_internal:DECODE_ERROR`. `tests/GenCerts.cpp` explicitly sets version 2 (= X.509 v3) on both the CA and provider certificates. If you write new cert-generation code, do the same.
- **BoringSSL is picky about PEM line endings.** CRLF-terminated PEM files from Windows sometimes fail to parse. Convert to LF before handing to `PEM_read_bio_X509` if you see mysterious decode errors.
- **Go and NASM are hard requirements for BoringSSL on Windows.** Without both on PATH, the depot build fails during BoringSSL's CMake configure step. Go is Google's build-and-test tool for the library; NASM compiles the assembly-optimized crypto primitives. `winget install GoLang.Go` handles Go; NASM via winget installs to `C:\Program Files\NASM\` but does not add itself to PATH ŌĆö add it manually via `[Environment]::SetEnvironmentVariable('Path', "$env:Path;C:\Program Files\NASM", 'User')` (then restart the shell).
- **Visual Studio Developer PowerShell clobbers user PATH.** `Launch-VsDevShell.ps1` replaces the process PATH with MSVC-specific entries, dropping user-persisted tool paths (Go, NASM, anything else). Symptom: `go version` / `nasm -v` work in a fresh PowerShell but fail in a VS Dev Shell. Fix: in the user's PowerShell profile (`$PROFILE` ŌåÆ `...\Documents\PowerShell\Microsoft.PowerShell_profile.ps1`), after the dev-shell init, re-merge persistent User + Machine PATH entries back into `$env:Path`. This makes Go + NASM (and the rest) available in every shell type. The profile fix is per-user and not in the Sneeze repo.
- **jwt-cpp's `find_package(OpenSSL)` does not work with BoringSSL.** BoringSSL's headers live in `openssl/` but are versioned differently from OpenSSL and do not include `opensslv.h` in the shape CMake expects. The depot bypasses jwt-cpp's CMake entirely with a custom `INSTALL_COMMAND` that just copies the headers. jwt-cpp is header-only, so no linking happens; `src/context/msf/` links BoringSSL directly.
- **`MSF::Sign()` output format is nested.** The payload JSON is wrapped as `{"data": "<original-json-string>"}` before signing, because jwt-cpp's `set_payload_claim()` expects claim-shaped data. The HTML viewer and `MSF::Parse()` unwrap this nesting on parse. If you change the payload shape in one place, change it in all three (signing tool, engine verifier, HTML viewer).
- **`MSF::CHAIN` loads the OS trust store on Windows.** It calls `CertOpenSystemStoreA("ROOT")` and walks every cert into the BoringSSL `X509_STORE`. This means chain validation respects Windows Update's root store updates automatically, but also means tests must use a fully self-signed chain ŌĆö you can't rely on the cert being "trusted" unless you inject the test CA into the store (tests don't, which is why the untrusted-chain test works as written).

### Build System

The project has **two fully independent CMake trees**, parameterized by `SNEEZE_CONFIG` (Debug/Release) and `SNEEZE_PLATFORM` (e.g., `windows-x64`). There is **no top-level `CMakeLists.txt`** that spans both ŌĆö that was deliberately removed. Dependencies are cloned once into `deps/repos/<Name>/` (shared across configs) and built+installed per config into `deps/builds/<platform>/<config>/libs/<Name>/` (per-config, since each dep is a separate `ExternalProject_Add` build that picks up `CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE` at configure time). Sneeze itself is a **single multi-config tree** at `builds/<platform>/build/` that emits into `builds/<platform>/install/{debug,release}/{lib,bin}/` ŌĆö the `install/<config>/` wrapper mirrors each dep's `libs/<Name>/install/{bin,lib}` layout for full symmetry. On Windows this means `Sneeze.sln` opens once and the Debug Ōåö Release dropdown in the IDE toolbar Just Works; on Linux/macOS the Ninja Multi-Config generator gives the same single-tree-two-configs behavior via `cmake --build --config`.

- **deps/CMakeLists.txt** ŌĆö standalone deps project. `cmake -S deps` builds all deps; `cmake -S deps -DDEP=<name>` builds one (CI path). Never references `src/`. Derives `SNEEZE_CONFIG`, `SNEEZE_PLATFORM`, `SNEEZE_DEP_REPO`, `LIBS_DIR` if not passed explicitly. Applies cross-dep ordering via `add_dependencies(...)`.
- **deps/*.cmake** ŌĆö one `ExternalProject_Add` per dep. Single source of truth; included by `deps/CMakeLists.txt`.
- **src/CMakeLists.txt** ŌĆö standalone Sneeze project. `cmake -S src`. Finds deps under `${LIBS_DIR}/<Name>/install/`. Forces `CMAKE_{ARCHIVE,LIBRARY,RUNTIME}_OUTPUT_DIRECTORY` (and the per-config `_DEBUG` / `_RELEASE` variants) to `${SNEEZE_BUILD_ROOT}/install/$<LOWER_CASE:$<CONFIG>>/{lib,bin}` so one build tree produces both configs into separate sibling `install/` trees (symmetric with each dep's `install/{bin,lib}`). `CMAKE_CONFIGURATION_TYPES` is pinned to `Debug;Release` **before** `project()` to keep VS/Xcode/Ninja-Multi-Config from probing `MinSizeRel`/`RelWithDebInfo` paths that don't exist in `deps/builds/<plat>/`. Never references `deps/`.
- **tests/CMakeLists.txt** ŌĆö defines the unified `SneezeTest` executable (all suite TUs + `TestRunner.cpp`) and the `GenCerts` tool; pulled in by `src/CMakeLists.txt`, inherits its multi-config output dirs. `SneezeTest` links only against `Sneeze` (all deps propagate transitively). Wasm and XR suites conditionally compiled via `SNEEZE_ENABLE_WASM` / `SNEEZE_ENABLE_XR`.
- **scripts/build-{windows.ps1,linux.sh,macos.sh}** ŌĆö the only glue between deps and Sneeze. Default (no flag): plain `cmake --build builds/<plat>/build --config <cfg>` (no dep checks, no configure). `-Deps` / `--deps`: `cmake -S deps` + stamped per-dep build loop against the per-config dep tree. `-All` / `--all`: deps flow, then `cmake -S src -B builds/<plat>/build` configure (Visual Studio generator on Windows, Ninja Multi-Config on Linux/macOS), then `cmake --build ŌĆ” --config <cfg>` to emit that config. `-Fresh` / `--fresh`: passes `cmake --fresh` (CMake 3.24+) to wipe `CMakeCache.txt` + `CMakeFiles/` before reconfiguring Sneeze. **Does NOT build** ŌĆö just regenerates the project files. Combine `-Fresh -Rebuild` for a fresh configure followed by a clean + build. Deps phase is skipped entirely. Use `-Fresh` when you want to be certain stale cache values (anari_DIR, compiler paths, toolchain tweaks) are gone; `-All`'s reconfigure stays non-destructive (idempotent cache update). `-Rebuild` / `--rebuild` is a **modifier, not a mode**: it composes with whatever target set the real mode flags pick out, and it **never crosses the src Ōåö deps wall on its own**. Alone ŌåÆ wipe + rebuild the Sneeze tree (`builds/<plat>/`, which includes both configs' install siblings and the shared `build/`). With `-Only <dep>` ŌåÆ scrub + rebuild that one dep. With `-Deps` ŌåÆ scrub + rebuild the entire per-config dep root. With `-All` ŌåÆ scrub + rebuild deps, then scrub + rebuild Sneeze. Source clones in `deps/repos/` are always preserved. `-Only` and `-List` imply deps mode; `-Rebuild` does NOT. `-Deps`, `-All`, and `-Fresh` are mutually exclusive; `-Rebuild` composes with any of them.
- **scripts/build-deps.sh** ŌĆö shared bash helper that drives `cmake -S deps` and the per-dep stamped loop on Linux/macOS; invoked by `build-linux.sh` and `build-macos.sh` when in deps mode.
- **Wasmtime** is built via `cargo build --release -p wasmtime-c-api` regardless of `SNEEZE_CONFIG` (Cargo release mode is always used; the product just gets copied into the config-specific install tree).
- **All other C/C++ dependencies** are built with CMake using `-DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=${SNEEZE_CONFIG}` and installed under their per-config `install/` prefixes.
- **vcpkg.json** is still provided as an alternative for developers who prefer vcpkg. The `USE_LOCAL_DEPS` option in `src/CMakeLists.txt` switches between `${LIBS_DIR}` paths and vcpkg paths.

