### Dependency Depot (Implemented)

**Status:** Implemented and operational. There is no top-level `CMakeLists.txt` ŌĆö deps and Sneeze are two fully independent CMake projects.

**Model.** Chromium's `depot_tools` / `third_party` separation, adapted for a single-repo layout. Two fully independent CMake trees, no top-level bridge; build scripts in `scripts/` are the sole glue.

**Canonical directory layout** (all under `Sneeze/`, all `deps/builds/` + `deps/repos/` + `builds/` are gitignored):

```
Sneeze/
Ōö£ŌöĆŌöĆ deps/
Ōöé   Ōö£ŌöĆŌöĆ CMakeLists.txt                    Standalone deps project (cmake -S deps)
Ōöé   Ōö£ŌöĆŌöĆ <dep>.cmake                       One ExternalProject_Add per dep
Ōöé   Ōö£ŌöĆŌöĆ repos/                            Shared source clones, reused across cfgs
Ōöé   Ōöé   Ōö£ŌöĆŌöĆ ANARI-SDK/
Ōöé   Ōöé   Ōö£ŌöĆŌöĆ Halogen/
Ōöé   Ōöé   Ōö£ŌöĆŌöĆ filament/
Ōöé   Ōöé   Ōö£ŌöĆŌöĆ Vox/
Ōöé   Ōöé   ŌööŌöĆŌöĆ ... (all other deps)
Ōöé   ŌööŌöĆŌöĆ builds/<platform>/<config>/       e.g. windows-x64/{debug,release}/
Ōöé       Ōö£ŌöĆŌöĆ build/                        Outer deps SuperBuild scratch + EP stamps
Ōöé       Ōöé   Ōö£ŌöĆŌöĆ .dep-stamps/              Script-level per-dep .done markers
Ōöé       Ōöé   ŌööŌöĆŌöĆ <dep>-prefix/             ExternalProject_Add's internal stamps
Ōöé       ŌööŌöĆŌöĆ libs/
Ōöé           ŌööŌöĆŌöĆ <Dep>/{build,install}/    Per-dep inner build + usable install
Ōö£ŌöĆŌöĆ src/                                  Standalone Sneeze project (cmake -S src)
Ōöé   ŌööŌöĆŌöĆ CMakeLists.txt
ŌööŌöĆŌöĆ builds/<platform>/                    Sneeze's own output (single multi-config tree)
    Ōö£ŌöĆŌöĆ build/                            Sneeze CMake scratch ŌĆö one tree, both configs
    ŌööŌöĆŌöĆ install/<config>/                 Per-config install; mirrors libs/<Dep>/install/
        Ōö£ŌöĆŌöĆ lib/                          Sneeze.lib / libSneeze.a
        ŌööŌöĆŌöĆ bin/                          Test executables + CLI tools
```

**Platform slugs:** `windows-x64`, `linux-x64`, `linux-arm64`, `macos-arm64`, `macos-x64`, `ios-arm64`, `android-arm64` ŌĆö must match `Artemis/pkg/manifest.json`. **Config** folder names are lowercased (`debug`/`release`) even though `CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE` is `Debug`/`Release`. **Single Sneeze build tree, two configs:** `builds/<platform>/build/` carries both Debug and Release; emission to `install/<config>/` is chosen per `cmake --build --config`. The deps side stays per-config because each dep is built by its own `ExternalProject_Add` invocation against a pinned `CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE`.

**Build commands (recommended entry point ŌĆö the `scripts/build-*` wrappers, which handle stamp bookkeeping and dep ordering):**

```powershell
# Windows (PowerShell)
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1                              # Sneeze only, Release (default)
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Config Debug                # Sneeze only, Debug
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Fresh                       # Reconfigure Sneeze (no build)
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Deps                        # Deps only (Release)
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Deps -Config Debug          # Deps only (Debug)
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -All                         # Deps, then Sneeze
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Only filament               # Build one dep if not cached (implies -Deps)
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Only filament -Rebuild      # Full-scrub rebuild of one dep
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Deps -Rebuild               # Full-scrub rebuild of all deps
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Rebuild                     # Full-scrub rebuild of SNEEZE ONLY (deps untouched)
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -All -Rebuild                # Full-scrub rebuild of deps + Sneeze
.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -List                        # Stamp cache state
```

```bash
# Linux / macOS (shell)
./scripts/build-linux.sh                                 # Sneeze only, Release (default)
./scripts/build-linux.sh --config Debug                  # Sneeze only, Debug
./scripts/build-linux.sh --fresh                         # Reconfigure Sneeze (no build)
./scripts/build-linux.sh --deps                          # Deps only
./scripts/build-linux.sh --all                           # Deps, then Sneeze
./scripts/build-linux.sh --only filament --rebuild       # full-scrub one dep
./scripts/build-linux.sh --deps --rebuild                # full-scrub all deps
./scripts/build-linux.sh --rebuild                       # full-scrub SNEEZE ONLY (deps untouched)
./scripts/build-linux.sh --all --rebuild                 # full-scrub deps + Sneeze
```

**Mode flags are mutually exclusive:** `-Deps`, `-All`, `-Fresh` ŌĆö only one at a time. `-Only` and `-List` implicitly enable deps mode. `-Rebuild` is a **modifier, not a mode** ŌĆö it composes with whichever target set the other flags pick, and on its own (no `-Deps`/`-Only`/`-All`) it operates on Sneeze alone and never touches `deps/`. Default (no flags) is Sneeze-only: plain `cmake --build builds/<plat>/build --config <cfg>` with no dep checks, no reconfigure. If the Sneeze build tree doesn't exist yet, the plain-build fails with "CMakeCache.txt missing" and the user must re-run with `-Fresh` (or `-All` if deps are also missing).

**Under the hood ŌĆö direct CMake invocations (used by CI):**

```bash
# All deps (any platform)
cmake -S deps -B deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/build \
   -DSNEEZE_CONFIG=<Debug|Release> \
   -DSNEEZE_PLATFORM=<plat> \
   -DSNEEZE_DEP_REPO=deps/repos \
   -DLIBS_DIR=deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/libs
cmake --build deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/build --config <cfg>

# Single dep (CI parallelization)
cmake -S deps -B deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/build -DDEP=<name> ...
cmake --build deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/build --target <name> --config <cfg>

# Sneeze (single multi-config tree; pass the Multi-Config generator on Unix)
cmake -S src -B builds/<plat>/build \
   -G "Ninja Multi-Config" \                             # omit on Windows (VS is default)
   -DLIBS_DIR=deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/libs \
   -DSNEEZE_CONFIG=<Debug|Release> \                     # seeds find_package
   -DSNEEZE_PLATFORM=<plat> \
   -DSNEEZE_BUILD_ROOT=builds/<plat>
cmake --build builds/<plat>/build --config <cfg>
```

**Hard separation invariant.** `deps/CMakeLists.txt` never reads from or writes under `src/`, and `src/CMakeLists.txt` never reads from or writes under `deps/` (it only consumes the installed headers + libs via `${LIBS_DIR}/<Name>/install/` paths passed in on the cmake command line). Neither file includes the other. This is a hard requirement. The scripts are the only glue: they orchestrate deps build, then Sneeze configure + build, as two separate cmake invocations.

**Script-level stamp system.** `scripts/build-windows.ps1` (and the `scripts/build-deps.sh` bash counterpart) maintain per-dep `.done` marker files under `<DepsBuildDir>/.dep-stamps/`. Once a dep builds successfully, its stamp is written and subsequent runs skip it. Stamps are orthogonal to `ExternalProject_Add`'s own internal step stamps (download/update/patch/configure/build/install).

**`-Rebuild` / `--rebuild` ŌĆö the full-scrub rebuild *modifier*.** The single, unambiguous "I don't care what state this was in, start over" escape hatch. Applies to whatever target set the other flags pick out. **Never crosses the src Ōåö deps wall on its own.** Behavior matrix:

| Invocation | Deps touched? | Sneeze touched? | What happens |
|---|---|---|---|
| `-Rebuild` alone | no | yes | Wipe `builds/<plat>/` (shared `build/` + both configs' `install/`), reconfigure, build Sneeze |
| `-Rebuild -Only <dep>` | that one dep | no | Scrub script stamp + EP prefix + `libs/<dep>/`; rebuild it |
| `-Rebuild -Deps` | all deps | no | Wipe entire per-config dep root (`deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/`); rebuild every dep |
| `-Rebuild -All` | all deps | yes | Deps scrub + rebuild, then Sneeze scrub + rebuild |

Source clones in `deps/repos/<dep>/` are **always** preserved ŌĆö filament alone takes 10+ min to re-clone, and local dev work on a clone should never be silently blown away. Deps-side scrub is implemented by the `Remove-DepState` helper (PowerShell) / `remove_dep_state` (bash); Sneeze-side scrub is a plain `Remove-Item`/`rm -rf` on `builds/<plat>/` (which wipes BOTH configs' install dirs, since the Sneeze tree is now a single multi-config tree).

`-Rebuild` is a pure modifier ŌĆö it can only touch `deps/` when `-Deps`, `-Only`, or `-All` is explicitly on the command line. On its own, it operates exclusively on the Sneeze tree.

**`Invalidate-DepConfigure` helper.** Before invoking `cmake --build --target <dep>`, the scripts explicitly delete `<DepsBuildDir>/<dep>-prefix/src/<dep>-stamp/<Config>/<dep>-configure` ŌĆö the ExternalProject configure-step stamp. This forces the inner configure to re-run on every invocation, so edits to `deps/<dep>.cmake` (changed CMAKE_ARGS, new BUILD_COMMAND, etc.) take effect without the developer having to manually delete build trees. Without this, a failed build whose configure previously succeeded would reuse the stale cached configure on retry.

**Configuration isolation (deps).** Debug and Release live in fully separate **deps** trees ŌĆö `deps/builds/<plat>/{debug,release}/`. No sharing of build outputs across configs. Every dep (including Filament + Halogen, post-PR-#15) tracks `SNEEZE_CONFIG`. The historical `LNK2038` mismatches between Halogen + Sneeze are now prevented by `deps/filament.cmake` disabling `FILAMENT_SHORTEN_MSVC_COMPILATION` on Debug and `deps/halogen.cmake` pinning `CMAKE_MSVC_RUNTIME_LIBRARY` per-config. See the "Halogen dependency chain" section above for details.

**Multi-config build (Sneeze standalone + Artemis consumer).** `src/CMakeLists.txt` carries a path generalization block that rewrites every dep path variable and every imported target (transitive across `anari::anari_static` + `vox::vox`) so they resolve at build time against `$<LOWER_CASE:$<CONFIG>>` instead of the single `SNEEZE_CONFIG` used at configure time. This lets **both** (a) Sneeze's standalone build at `builds/<plat>/build/` and (b) Artemis's consumer tree (via `add_subdirectory`) produce Debug and Release from a single CMake tree ŌĆö one `.sln` on Windows (VS dropdown flips configs), Ninja Multi-Config on Linux/macOS, `cmake --build ŌĆ” --config <cfg>` to pick which config emits. `CMAKE_CONFIGURATION_TYPES` is pinned to `Debug;Release` *before* `project()` so VS/Xcode/Ninja-MC don't probe `MinSizeRel` / `RelWithDebInfo` paths that don't exist under `deps/builds/<plat>/`. The rewriter has a `_sneeze_resolve_variant` helper that probes disk for Debug-suffix filename variants (`libcurl-d.lib`, `openxr_loaderd.lib`, `spirv-cross-cored.lib`) because simple `/release/` Ōåö `/debug/` substitution doesn't handle those name changes. Active whenever `USE_LOCAL_DEPS` is on (the default for both standalone and consumer). Output dirs (`CMAKE_{ARCHIVE,LIBRARY,RUNTIME}_OUTPUT_DIRECTORY` and their `_DEBUG` / `_RELEASE` variants) all point into `${SNEEZE_BUILD_ROOT}/install/$<LOWER_CASE:$<CONFIG>>/{lib,bin}`, keeping the two configs in sibling install trees under a shared build root.

**Source clones are shared.** `deps/repos/<Name>/` is a single git checkout per dep, reused across Debug and Release builds. Saves disk and clone time.

**Caveats:**
- To force a single dep to re-clone: delete `deps/repos/<name>/` (usually unnecessary ŌĆö set `GIT_TAG` and let ExternalProject handle it).
- To force a single dep to fully rebuild: `.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Only <name> -Rebuild -Config <cfg>` (scrubs the script stamp, the ExternalProject prefix, and the per-dep `libs/<name>/` build + install trees; next invoke re-downloads/patches/configures/builds/installs top-to-bottom).
- Stale CMake caches in inner dep build dirs can silently resolve to wrong paths (see the `find_package` caveat in Known Gotchas). Nuking `deps/builds/<plat>/<cfg>/libs/<Name>/build/` is the escape hatch.

**Developer workflow:**
- **First build:** run `-All` once per config ŌĆö deps (~35-90 min) then Sneeze (~1-2 min). Day-to-day work never touches the deps phase.
- **Day-to-day:** plain `.\scripts\build-windows.ps1` (seconds). No CMake, no dep checks, just compile + link Sneeze.
- **After editing CMakeLists.txt:** `.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Fresh` to reconfigure Sneeze only (does NOT build). Follow with a plain `.\scripts\build-windows.ps1` to build, or use `-Fresh -Rebuild` to combine reconfigure + clean + build.
- **What `-Fresh` actually does (precisely):** passes `cmake --fresh` (3.24+), which wipes `CMakeCache.txt` + the `CMakeFiles/` directory before rerunning configure. It does **not** build or delete compiled `.obj` / `.lib` / `.dll` outputs. Scope is always Sneeze-only; the dependency libs under `deps/builds/` are never touched by `-Fresh`. For a true from-zero rebuild of everything: `-All -Rebuild` in one shot (scrubs + rebuilds deps then scrubs + rebuilds Sneeze).
- **After pulling a new dep version:** `.\scripts\build-windows.ps1 -Only <name> -Rebuild` forces that one dep to rebuild from scratch while every other dep stays cached.

**Recommended daily workflow on Windows ŌĆö use Visual Studio, not the scripts.** Once `-All` has produced a configured Sneeze tree, the CMake machinery has already generated a full `.sln` at `builds\windows-x64\build\Sneeze.sln` (single file, multi-config). For day-to-day "I edited a `.cpp`, rebuild" work, open the solution in Visual Studio and use F7 ŌĆö incremental builds are faster than re-invoking the scripts, and you get the debugger, breakpoints, IntelliSense, Error List, and the rest of the IDE for free. The Debug Ōåö Release dropdown in the toolbar flips configs without reopening; outputs land in `install\debug\{bin,lib}` or `install\release\{bin,lib}` accordingly. The scripts exist for the cases Visual Studio can't solve: CI, Linux/macOS builds, fresh-checkout smoke tests, and reconfigure after editing `CMakeLists.txt` (which is what `-Fresh` is for). The rule of thumb: **fresh-checkout / config-changes / cross-platform ŌåÆ scripts; daily editing ŌåÆ `.sln` in VS.** Same deal on macOS with the Xcode project CMake produces, and on Linux with Ninja Multi-Config + your editor of choice. CMake's command-line UX is legitimately rough; nobody should have to live in it day-to-day.

## Naming Rationale ŌĆö CONTROL, AGENT, SILO

ENGINE has three subordinate classes: **CONTROL**, **NETWORK**, and **STORAGE**. The names are deliberately symmetric ŌĆö short, noun-form, parallel structure.

**CONTROL** (`sneeze/control/`) owns the engine thread, pool vector, metronome, and job queues. **POOL** is the non-template base managing agents and Hz-driven tick. **POOL_QUEUE<JOB_PTR>** adds typed job queues. **AGENT** is the abstract base class for engine threads (COMPOSITOR, SCRUB, FETCH, C). The CONTROL/AGENT pairing echoes the TV show "Get Smart" ŌĆö an intentional pop-culture nod that also happens to be the right name. CONTROL is symmetric with NETWORK and STORAGE; AGENT accurately describes what the threads are (autonomous units acting on behalf of the engine).

**STORAGE::SILO** groups four `STORAGE::UNIT`s for a single container. "Silo" captures the isolation semantics ŌĆö storage silos are departmentally isolated from each other within the browser, with no crossover between containers. `NETWORK::ASSET` is a different concept (a cached URL resource, not an isolated data store) and is unchanged.

## MBE Runtime Pipeline ŌĆö Remaining Work

The following items were discussed during the MBE architecture sessions but are not yet implemented or not yet wired up. The building blocks (classes, methods, data structures) exist for most of these ŌĆö what's missing is the integration code that connects them.

### Wiring and Orchestration

1. ~~**Fabric instantiation orchestration**~~ ŌĆö **DONE.** Full end-to-end pipeline operational. CONTAINER creates a WASM_STORE on `Open()` with linker initialized (32 host functions). `Fabric.cpp`'s `OnMsfReady` path enumerates modules from the parsed MSF, creates a `WASM_FETCH` per module (URL + SRI hash from the MSF payload), on successful fetch calls `CONTAINER::Instance_Open(twFabricIx, sUrl, sHash, aWasmBytes)` which compiles the WASM bytecode and instantiates it via linker. `Instance_Open` calls `CallInit()` and `CallOpen(twFabricIx)` after successful instantiation. Verified working with `solar_system.wasm` ŌĆö the WASM module's `Open` export calls `Scene.Node_Root` and `Scene.Node_Open` host functions to create 4 scene nodes (Root, Sun, Earth, Moon) with position, radius, and color data via the RMCOBJECT wire format. Nodes are rendered by the compositor. Successfully opened instances tracked in `m_aModule` and closed symmetrically in `~Impl`. **Test data:** `tests/data/solar-system.msf` is a signed MSF referencing `solar_system.wasm` at `https://cdn.rp1.com/test/solar_system.wasm` with SHA-256 hash verification. `astro::InjectSolarSystem` call in `Fabric.cpp` is currently commented out ŌĆö WASM module populates the scene instead.

2. ~~**FABRIC -> WASM_STORE typed connection**~~ ŌĆö **DONE.** CONTAINER owns `DEP::WASM_STORE*` (created in `Open()`, closed in `Close()`). FABRIC accesses the store through its CONTAINER (`pFabric->Container()->...`). The old `void* m_pOwner` in Fabric is no longer needed for this purpose.

3. **EVENT_SYSTEM not connected** -- The event system (Watch_Node, Watch_Tree, Fire_*) exists as a standalone class but: (a) there is no `EVENT_SYSTEM` instance in the engine, (b) `NODE::Node_Add`/`Node_Remove` don't call `Fire_NodeAdded`/`Fire_NodeRemoved`, (c) no code calls `Fire_NodeModified` on property writes. Needs an engine-owned instance and wiring into the SOM mutators.

4. **SPATIAL_INDEX not connected** ŌĆö `SPATIAL_INDEX` exists but nothing collects SOM nodes into a flat list and calls `Build()`, and nothing calls `QueryFrustum`/`QuerySphere`. Needs integration into the compositor (frustum culling) and potentially a host function for proximity queries.

5. **THREAD_POOL not connected** ŌĆö `THREAD_POOL` exists but is not instantiated by `WASM_RUNTIME` or `ENGINE`. No work is submitted to it. Needs initialization during engine startup and work dispatch from WASM store execution paths.

6. ~~**Host function linker registration**~~ ŌĆö **DONE.** `WASM_STORE::InitializeLinker()` creates a `wasmtime_linker_t` and registers all 32 host functions (Console 14, Storage 6, Scene 10, Timer 2) via `RegisterFunc()`. Host functions receive `WASM_STORE*` as `pEnv`, bridge to CONTEXT via `GetHostData()`.

7. **Host function implementations** ŌĆö **Partial.** Scene host functions `Scene_Node_Root` and `Scene_Node_Open` are fully implemented ŌĆö they read RMCOBJECT from WASM linear memory (via wasmtime memory export), construct MAP_OBJECT_CELESTIAL instances from the wire format, create NODEs in the SOM via `CONTAINER::Node_Root`/`Node_Open`, and return `twObjectIx` handles to WASM. `Scene_Node_Close` implemented. Remaining Scene functions (Position, Scale, Bound, Color, Name, Radius, Texture) are stubbed. Console host functions use `ENGINE::Log()` as a temporary placeholder (correct routing through CONSOLE::STREAM pending). Storage and Timer host functions are stubbed. `ReadWasmString()` utility for reading strings from WASM linear memory is implemented. Each remaining implementation needs access control checks (via `AccessControl.h`).

### Features Not Yet Started

8. ~~**Cache -> HTTP integration**~~ ŌĆö **Done.** MANAGER::FetchEntry() uses libcurl directly to stream downloads to disk on background threads. HTTP status checked (2xx only), redirects followed, 300s timeout.

9. ~~**Module hash validation**~~ ŌĆö **Done.** SRI-format hashes (sha256/sha384/sha512) parsed and verified via BoringSSL EVP_Digest. Hash mismatch -> FAILED, file deleted. Persistent entries verified on fetch; unhashed entries can be upgraded.

10. **AgentAnimator** ŌĆö Discussed as a dedicated 64Hz animator thread that traverses the SOM and interpolates animation state on map objects. `AGENT::B` was repurposed as `AGENT::SCRUB` (disk cleanup). The animator role will be assigned to a different placeholder agent (`AGENT::E` at 64Hz is a natural fit). Needs: rename, SOM traversal, animation data model on MAP_OBJECT, interpolation logic.

11. **WASM CPU budgeting (fuel metering)** ŌĆö Wasmtime fuel metering is proven in WasmTest but not wired into store creation. Each store should have a configurable fuel budget.

12. **WASM memory caps** ŌĆö Per-store linear memory limits. Not implemented.

13. **Overlay fabrics** ŌĆö The root fabric structure supports overlay siblings alongside the primary fabric, but no overlay nodes are created or managed.

### Teardown Gaps

14. **Teardown phase 2 (Communicate)** ŌĆö Currently a log line. Needs to actually await async acknowledgements from active WASM instances before proceeding to phase 3.

15. **Teardown instance lifecycle** ŌĆö `DestroyAllStores` deletes stores (destructor deletes instances), but it doesn't call `CallClose`/`CallShutdown` on active instances before destruction. The proper sequence is: CallClose on all open fabrics per instance, then CallShutdown on each active instance, then destroy the store.

### Future Milestone: Loading a Spatial Fabric

The ultimate integration test is loading one or more real `.msf` files containing WASM modules, instantiating them into stores, and having them manipulate the SOM through host functions. This requires most of the above items to be complete (especially #1, #6, #7, #8, #9) plus MSF payload parsing for the WASM module manifest.

